Even thoughts of home bring the soldiers in ‘Exposure’ little comfort. The phrase “crickets jingle”
evokes memories of English summers, with the onomatopoeic “jingle” mimicking the noise of the
insects. However, the harsh ‘ck’ sound and assonant short ‘i’ sounds add an element of discomfort
and monotony to the memory that is far removed from the joyful sounds generally associated with
‘jingling’. This heightens the sense that thinking of home only compounds the soldiers’ misery.
